# gitleaks finding fingerprints: <commit-sha>:<path>:<rule-id>:<line>
#
# Each entry suppresses ONE finding in ONE historical commit. Entries are commit-pinned,
# so a new occurrence of the same string in any new commit still fails the gate. This is
# deliberately not a pattern allowlist: an allowlist broad enough to pass test fixtures
# would be broad enough to pass a real leak, and CLAUDE.md makes secret hygiene
# non-negotiable.
#
# CI runs `gitleaks git --log-opts=--all`, which scans every commit on every branch. A
# planted leak-test secret therefore fails the quality gate on unrelated PRs, and renaming
# it in a later commit does not help — the original commit stays reachable.
#
# Both entries below are the same M1-301 leak-test fixture, `sk-live-planted-9d2f1a`,
# flagged as generic-api-key because `sk-live-` is a realistic key prefix and its entropy
# is 3.879. It was never a credential. M1-301 renamed it to the low-entropy form
# `privateFAKE123456` (which the scanner correctly ignores), so no new commit contains the
# old value and this list is closed — it needs no additions.
#
# Lesson for future leak tests: a planted secret must be distinctive in program output,
# not realistic-looking. Use the FAKE-infix low-entropy form.

